The median minimizes the sum of absolute distances to all points in the dataset.

Formally, if you pick any value x, and compute:  ∑∣ai−x∣
then this sum is minimum when x is the median.

Whenever you see:
“minimize sum of distances”
“operations = |a[i] - x|”
“make all equal with minimum moves”
👉 Immediately think:
Sort → Median → Answer

🟢 Case 1: Odd number of points
Example:
Points:
1, 3, 5
Sorted already.
👉 Median = 3

🟢 Case 2: Even number of points
Example:
Points:
1, 3, 5, 7
👉 Two medians:
Lower median = 3
Upper median = 5
🔑 Important fact:
👉 Any value between 3 and 5 gives the SAME minimum cost



⚡ 1. Classic Problem: Minimum Moves to Equal Array
Problem:
You can increment/decrement any element by 1.
Find minimum operations to make all elements equal.
Solution:
Target value = median
Answer = sum of absolute differences

⚡ 2. 1D Facility Location Problem
Problem:
You want to place a warehouse on a number line so that total distance to all houses is minimum.
Insight:
👉 Place it at the median location

⚡ 4. Minimum Cost to Align Points
Problem:
Given points on a line, make them all equal with minimum cost.
👉 Same pattern:
If cost = absolute difference → median
If cost = squared difference → mean
